00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,320
Same code. Different config per environment. Config maps make that work. Picture this database

2
00:00:10,320 --> 00:00:17,240
host equals local host hardcoded in your app. Works in dev breaks in production. The fix

3
00:00:17,240 --> 00:00:23,760
seems obvious, bake config into the image. But then every environment change means a

4
00:00:23,760 --> 00:00:30,840
build. Config map breaks that cycle. It stores configuration outside your container image

5
00:00:30,840 --> 00:00:38,440
as key value pairs. Once you have a config map, pods consume it three ways. First, environment

6
00:00:38,440 --> 00:00:45,120
variables inject values directly into the container. Second, command line arguments pass

7
00:00:45,120 --> 00:00:51,680
config values as flags at startup. Third, files mounted in a volume. Drop a whole settings

8
00:00:51,680 --> 00:00:59,520
file at a path like slash etc slash config slash settings dot yaml. Four rules before you use

9
00:00:59,520 --> 00:01:07,040
them. Not for secrets, there is no encryption, never store passwords here. Size cap one megabyte,

10
00:01:07,040 --> 00:01:14,080
bigger than that use a volume or external storage. Namespace scoped. The config map must

11
00:01:14,080 --> 00:01:21,400
live in the same namespace as the pod. Since version one, 19, you can mark a config map immutable.

12
00:01:21,400 --> 00:01:29,720
No accidental overwrites. Lighter on the API server. One image. Three environments. Three

13
00:01:29,720 --> 00:01:35,200
config maps. Zero rebuilds. Kubernetes dot config maps.

